            <h3>Delhi</h3>


            <h4>Jantar Mantar</h4>
            <p>As an equinoctial sundial and observatory with thirteen incredible astronomical apparatuses constructed on an unfathomable size, Jantar Mantar is one of the top family-friendly destinations in Delhi.</p>


            <h4>Humayun Tomb</h4>
            <p>Humayun's Tomb is a 16th-century garden tomb designed by Persian architects on commission by Humayun's wife, Bega Begum. It serves as a model for the opulent Mughal architecture that would become popular in succeeding generations.</p>


            <h4>Red Fort</h4>
            <p>This complex of red sandstone and marble, constructed by Shah Jahan in 1639, is filled with tales of victory and defeat, grandeur and deceit. In terms of architecture, this UNESCO World Heritage Site is a timeless representation of Mughal architecture infused with characteristics of Central Asian and Indian architecture.</p>

            <h3>Indore</h3>


            <h4>Rajwada</h4>
            <p>The magnificent Rajwaada Palace, often regarded as the most prominent tourist destination in Indore, is renowned worldwide for its unparalleled magnificence and extravagance. The palace is a seven-story, 200-year-old structure with a beautifully landscaped garden that includes artificial waterfalls and fountains.</p>


            <h4>Lal Bagh Palace</h4>
            <p>The Lal Bagh Palace, home to the Holkar dynasty's monarchs, is the epitome of elegance and majesty. The 28-acre palace showcases the taste of the Holkar dynasty's monarchs.</p>


            <h4>Patalpani Waterfalls</h4>
            <p>The Patalpani Waterfall is a well-liked picnic location for the locals and is situated in the Mhow Tehsil of the Indore district. Encircled by towering hills and thick forests, Patalpani plunges to a depth of 300 meters.</p>

